00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:16.930
&gt;&gt; Todd Harvey: Good
morning, good morning.

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:20.770
I take the podium in gratitude,
and I think that you know why.

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:24.690
It's because we work
in the same field

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:30.380
and that is preserving tradition
and continuing tradition.

00:03:30.380 --> 00:03:35.120
And I do it from my place, which
is to take care of the stuff.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:37.970
And you do it out there
in the world.

00:03:37.970 --> 00:03:41.190
And we're all part
of the same process.

00:03:41.190 --> 00:03:50.290 position:56%
I have a few words that I think will
help us focus on the talks today.

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:57.050
And I get to talk about
the Library of Congress

00:03:57.050 --> 00:04:03.200
which is the oldest federal
institution, cultural institution.

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:05.800
The world's preeminent
reservoir of knowledge,

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:08.740
providing unparalleled
integrated resources

00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:11.530 position:56%
to Congress and the American people.

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:13.510
That's the big bold:
the American people.

00:04:13.510 --> 00:04:18.390
Founded in 1800, the library seeks
to further human understanding,

00:04:18.390 --> 00:04:21.680
wisdom, by providing
access to knowledge

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:24.910 position:56%
through its magnificent collections.

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:27.620
So we are the largest
library in the world,

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:29.310
which means we have
the largest collection

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:32.890
of storytelling in
the world by default.

00:04:32.890 --> 00:04:36.850
And most of those are here at
the American Folk Life Center.

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:40.850 position:56%
So let me tell you, the American
Folk Life Center was created in 1976

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:45.180 position:56%
by an act of Congress, through
programs of research, documentation,

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:49.980 position:56%
archival preservation, reference
service, live performance, exhibits,

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:51.650
publications and training.

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:55.510
The American Folk Life Center
archive, established by the Library

00:04:55.510 --> 00:04:58.700
of Congress Music Division in 1928,

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:02.880
is now one of the world's largest
archives of ethnographic materials

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:05.900
from the United States
and around the world.

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:09.970
Most of our materials and
our programs and our services

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:15.530
to you are found on our website,
and it's a great thing to explore.

00:05:15.530 --> 00:05:19.180
You can waste hours and
hours of time looking at it.

00:05:19.180 --> 00:05:24.640
I curate the Lomax Collections here
at the American Folk Life Center.

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:29.920
And they are some of the
earliest documentation.

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:32.780
The Lomax's ran our
archive in the 1930's.

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:36.070
And so what I thought I would
do, just to start things off,

00:05:36.070 --> 00:05:41.580
is to play a couple of
examples of Lomax materials.

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:46.440
This isn't strictly storytelling,
but it's personal narrative.

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:48.770
It's spoken word materials.

00:05:48.770 --> 00:05:52.510
And I think it will
give you some insight

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:55.400
into what we have in
our collections.

00:05:55.400 --> 00:06:00.750
And so the Lomax's,
here's Mr. Lomax,

00:06:00.750 --> 00:06:03.400 position:56%
John Lomax with an unidentified man.

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:06.160
Maybe someone will know who he is.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.040
Probably somewhere in Georgia.

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:15.390
Here's the younger
Lomax, with Sonny Terry

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:19.350
and Brownie McGhee, these guys.

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:24.490
Recording girls singing
in San Antonio 1934.

00:06:24.490 --> 00:06:27.860
Alan Lomax in action in the 1980's,

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:31.980 position:56%
explaining to the world why
cultural equity is the way we should

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:33.800
all live.

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:35.510
So I want to play you an example.

00:06:35.510 --> 00:06:39.800
This is [inaudible] since 1939.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:45.290
